My most recent episode on my dating life and more importantly, how to find a therapist 😇 I don’t pretend to be a licensed professional, I’m just a mentally ill person who shares her experiences online.

I cannot stress enough how finding the RIGHT therapist has changed my life. It took a lot of trial and error and there were many years I felt like giving up. If you feel like you’re hitting a wall with your current therapist, maybe it’s time for a change. Therapy is also more accessible than ever with online therapy options, zoom, etc and guess what, it’s not only for people who are struggling!! It’s a really great way to have someone help you be held accountable, figure out what your goals are, and live a more purposeful life.
On today’s episode I sat down with @loveisblindnetflix alum @lifewithdeeps to discuss internalized racism, how it’s affected her dating life, and the complexities of growing up between two cultures.

This week’s episode is all about Dissociative Identity Disorder, previously known as multiple personality disorder. It is a condition characterized by the presence of two or more distinct personality states, or “alters.” The disorder arises as a response to childhood trauma — each alter may have a unique name, personal history, and characteristics. 

I am joined by Ella  @dissociation.info , who lives with over 30 alters. We discuss their diagnosis, life with alternate personalities, and how they’ve used Instagram to debunk myths around DID.

#did #dissociativeidentitydisorder #dissociation #mentalhealthawareness

Today’s epsiode I am joined by @camimendes 🌟 We discuss everything from eating disorders to representation in film and how to maintain your sanity in the public eye. Thank you Cami for opening up to me and trusting me with this episode 🙏

75% of women in the US report having an unhealthy relationship with food. 67% of women are trying to actively lose weight. In the era of social media, it seems diet culture is more prevalent than ever. I love that Cami is open about her struggles and that the help she received worked!! If you struggle with unhealthy thoughts, feelings, or behaviors related to food or your body, I want to remind you that help is available. ♥️

Source: University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill

On today’s episode, @iamchrissyking and I discuss the toxic wellness community, diet culture, body image, fatphobia and so much more! This is such an important topic that doesn’t get nearly enough attention. I’m constantly inundated with marketing from influencers and corporations promoting products that prey on my insecurities and tell me I’m ugly and should hate the way I look 😭 Thank you Chrissy for speaking absolute facts! I learned so much and this episode left me with so much to think about.

Today’s episode philosopher C. Thi Nguyen opened my eyes to our entire lives being gamified in ways we don’t realize. He showed me that it’s not just social media that’s changing the way we act and think, it’s everything being quantified. Stock market, medical institutions filling quota, higher education, etc, etc. We also discussed parenthood, echo chambers, and food porn.

It’s World Mental Health Month and I’m back at McLean for the first time since I was a patient 🥲
I am forever indebted to this place and can’t wait to pay it forward. I spent the day with McLean faculty and community members, to discuss the best plan of action in continuing the fight against mental illness. I am also speaking to patients tomorrow about my experience, which is surreal.

Mental illness is the leading cause of disability in the world with two thirds of people with diagnosable mental disorders not receiving treatment. Part of this is due to accessibility and also stigma. Everyday I count my lucky stars that I received a proper diagnosis and was able to get help. I am so proud to join McLean’s Women’s Council and begin my involvement with the hospital that saved my life. So much more to come ❤️

New episode on UTIs with urologist Dr. Angelish Kumar.  I think every single one of my girlfriends has suffered from a UTI at some point. Last week, I went on a quick trip to Boston for McLean's Annual Dinner. I feel incredibly grateful to be a part of this amazing community of former patients, clinicians, researchers, donors, and family members of those who have been touched by mental illness. 

What’s truly special about McLean is that even though each person has their own unique experience, there's this undeniable sense of connection and understanding when you walk through those doors. It's like, you don't have to explain yourself because everyone just gets it. McLean has been an unwavering source of support for me, providing the kind of care and understanding that I desperately needed, even after my discharge.

I want to give a heartfelt thank you to all the doctors and staff members at McLean who have dedicated their lives to making a difference in the world of mental health, while working within a very broken system. You have created a safe haven where people feel understood, valued, and can work on getting healthy and back to their lives. ❤️

Pictured with Dr. David Alperovitz (Director of the Klarman Eating Disorders Center), Diane Davey (Director of the Obsessive Compulsive Disorder Institute) and Dr. Karen Jacob (Director of the Gunderson Residence for Personality Disorders)
